| Notes                   = * {{WP|Chadwick Boseman}} was scheduled to reprise his lead role as [[T'Challa (Earth-199999)|Black Panther]] for this film, before his death on August 28, 2020. Following Boseman's death, there were no plans to recast the role nor to use CGI to replicate his likeness in any capacity.{{cite|ref=true|refname=Shareholder|url= https://www.marvel.com/articles/movies/black-panther-2-wakanda|title= ‘Black Panther 2' Will Explore the World of Wakanda|work= Marvel.com|last= Paige|first= Rachel|date= December 10, 2020|accessdate= December 11, 2020}}{{cite|ref=true|refname=World of Wakanda|url= https://deadline.com/2021/01/marvel-kevin-feige-interview-wandavision-black-panther-2-chadwick-boseman-black-widow-disney-1234670774/|title= Marvel Boss Kevin Feige On ‘Black Panther 2’ Post Boseman, ‘Black Widow’ Release & Why Streaming Plans Won’t Burn MCU At The B.O.|work= Deadline|last= D'Alessandro|first= Anthony|date= January 11, 2021|accessdate= January 11, 2021}}
* Originally slated to be released on May 6, 2022, this film was later pushed back to July 8, 2022.<ref name="Shareholder"/> The release date was later taken by {{ml|Thor: Love and Thunder}}, pushing this film back to November 11, 2022, taking the release date of {{ml|The Marvels (film)}}.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://variety.com/2021/film/news/disney-delays-doctor-strange-thor-black-panther-1235091673/|title= Disney Delays ‘Doctor Strange 2,’ ‘Thor 4,’ ‘Black Panther’ Sequel and ‘Indiana Jones 5’|work= Variety|last= Rubin|first= Rebecca|date= October 18, 2021|accessdate= October 18, 2021}}
* Marvel Studios President [[Kevin Feige]] stated that the primary goal of the sequel has always been to further the mythology of [[Wakanda]] by exploring its different subcultures and characters.<ref name="World of Wakanda"/>

